The Act is titled the "Elie Wiesel Genocide and Atrocities Prevention Act of 2018". Congress acknowledges the importance of preventing genocide and atrocities. The "Elie Wiesel Genocide and Atrocities Prevention Act of 2018" emphasizes the significance of the United States Government's efforts in atrocity prevention and response through interagency coordination. It calls for regular monitoring of global developments that increase the risk of atrocities, identifying gaps in foreign policy, enhancing capacity for prevention and response, and providing recommendations to improve related policies and resources. The "Elie Wiesel Genocide and Atrocities Prevention Act of 2018" aims to enhance atrocity prevention and response by improving policies, programs, resources, and tools. It involves outreach to NGOs and civil society, regular consultation with relevant federal agencies, and ensuring resources are available for prevention and response efforts. The "Elie Wiesel Genocide and Atrocities Prevention Act of 2018" aims to enhance atrocity prevention and response by improving policies, programs, resources, and tools. SEC. 3. STATEMENT OF POLICY. The United States aims to prevent atrocities by working with partners and allies to address causes such as insecurity, displacement, and violent conflict. A government-wide strategy includes strengthening diplomatic capacities and using foreign assistance effectively to respond urgently to risks of atrocities. The United States aims to prevent atrocities by responding early and effectively, strengthening diplomatic response, supporting local civil society, promoting financial transparency, and using various means to prevent and respond to atrocities. The United States aims to prevent atrocities by responding early and effectively, strengthening diplomatic response, supporting local civil society, promoting financial transparency, and using various means to prevent and respond to atrocities, including multilateral efforts to prevent and respond to atrocities by prioritizing timely diplomatic efforts and promoting international cooperation. SEC. 4. TRAINING OF FOREIGN SERVICE OFFICERS IN CONFLICT AND ATROCITIES PREVENTION. Section 708 of the Foreign Service Act of 1980 is amended to include training for Foreign Service Officers assigned to countries at risk of mass atrocities. This training includes recognizing escalation patterns, early warning signs, and methods to prevent and respond to atrocities. The curr_chunk discusses conflict assessment methods, peacebuilding, mediation, prevention, early action, response, and transitional justice measures to address atrocities. SEC. 5. REPORTS. The President must provide annual reports to specific committees on efforts to prevent and respond to atrocities, including analysis of capacities and constraints for detection, early warning, response, information-sharing, planning, and coordination. The annual reports must include recommendations to strengthen US capabilities for atrocities prevention, details on funding spent by relevant federal departments, a global assessment of ongoing atrocities, and the efficacy of any actions taken. The annual reports must include recommendations to strengthen US capabilities for atrocities prevention, details on funding spent by relevant federal departments, a global assessment of ongoing atrocities, and the efficacy of any steps taken by the Board or relevant Federal agency to respond to such atrocities. Recommendations should also ensure shared responsibility by enhancing multilateral mechanisms for preventing atrocities. The report required by subsection (a) will cover the involvement of financial institutions in conflict prevention, mitigation, and response, as well as strengthening regional organizations. It will also address the implementation status of previous recommendations and identify the Federal agencies and consulted organizations. The report will consider recommendations from civil society, academic, and other non-governmental organizations to prevent and respond to atrocities. It will be made available to all members of Congress. SEC. 6. DEFINITIONS.

    In this Act--
            (1) "genocide" means an offense under section 1091 of title 18, United States Code;
            (2) "atrocities" means war crimes, crimes against humanity, and genocide;
            (3) "transitional justice" means measures used by countries transitioning from conflict or repressive regimes to address atrocities and promote peace;
            (4) "war crime" has the meaning in section 2441(c) of title 18, United States Code.

SEC. 7. RULE OF CONSTRUCTION.

    This Act does not authorize the use of military force.

            Passed the Senate December 12, 2018. The Senate passed S. 1158 on December 12, 2018, an act aimed at enhancing US Government capacities to prevent, mitigate, and respond to acts of genocide and other atrocity crimes that threaten national and international security.
